- Thu 16 Aug 2018. News Scan. Ebola total grows
[CIDRAP (Center for Infectious Disease Reporting and Policy), edited]
http://www.cidrap.umn.edu/news-perspective/2018/08/news-scan-aug-16-2018

The Democratic Republic of the Congo (DRC) Ministry of Health (MOH) released a new update late yesterday [15 Aug 2018] afternoon on the growing Ebola outbreak in the eastern region of the country, noting 7 new confirmed cases, one of whom is a healthcare worker at Mangina Reference Health Center.

The outbreak total now stands at 73 cases, of which 46 are confirmed and 27 are probable. In addition, 43 deaths have been reported, and health officials are investigating 40 suspected cases. All 7 new cases are from Mabalako and involve probable and known contacts of previously confirmed cases.

Yesterday, the MOH confirmed that ring vaccination began in the affected health zone of Ituri province. Earlier this week, Ituri confirmed 6 cases of Ebola, including one death. ...[more]

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail Rapporteur Mary Marshall

- Thu 16 Aug 2018. MSF opens Ebola treatment center in response to outbreak in North Kivu
[Doctors Without Borders/MSF, edited]
https://www.doctorswithoutborders.org/what-we-do/news-stories/news/drc-msf-opens-ebola-treatment-center-response-outbreak-north-kivu

The international medical humanitarian organization Doctors Without Borders / Médecins Sans Frontières (MSF) opened an Ebola treatment center on Tue 14 Aug [2018] in Mangina, a small town considered to be the epicenter of the outbreak in North Kivu, Democratic Republic of Congo (DRC). A total of 37 patients are currently hospitalized in this facility, with 31 of those cases confirmed and 6 suspected.

"Among our patients, we have several colleagues from the Congolese health system," said Gwenola Seroux, MSF emergency programs coordinator. "They were the first to respond, and some were exposed to the virus."

Before this center opened, MSF was working in an isolation unit in the area to improve safety and implement protection measures. All patients from that unit have been transferred to the new Ebola treatment center.

To address some of the response priorities set by health authorities, MSF is working along the route between Mambasa and Makeke in Ituri province, visiting health centers to set up isolation rooms, undertaking surveillance activities, and liaising with community health workers to raise awareness about Ebola. Infection prevention and control protocols are also being reinforced in the region -- and in MSF's existing non-Ebola projects in the area -- to prevent further spread of Ebola, which is a critical pillar of the Ebola outbreak response.

In neighboring Uganda, MSF is part of the national task force to ensure effective preparations are in place to tackle the risk of cross-border contagion. ...[more]

