[2] Recommendations
- Wed 15 Aug 2018. Opinion | Ebola responders must learn language lessons from the 2014 epidemic
[IRIN, edited]
https://www.irinnews.org/opinion/2018/08/15/opinion-ebola-responders-language-epidemic-congo-africa
[Byline: Aimee Ansari]

Amid the [West African] epidemic, UNICEF and Catholic Relief Services published ominous survey results: In Sierra Leone, one of the hardest-hit countries, 30% of respondents believed Ebola was transmitted by mosquitoes; another 30% believed it was an airborne disease. Moreover, around 4 of 10 respondents (42%) believed hot salt-water baths were an effective cure.

Many reports evaluating how different agencies responded to the epidemic pointed to a lack of community engagement or understanding of local culture as key early failures. A big part of that failure was the inability of aid workers to converse in local languages.

In the 3 most affected countries -- Guinea, Liberia, and Sierra Leone -- people speak more than 90 languages. Literacy levels are low, especially in the official national languages (French and English), and yet Ebola-related materials were mostly in written form in those languages. This early shortage of information for non-literate people and speakers of minority languages left significant swathes of the population in deadly ignorance.

ACAPS, a non-profit group specialising in research and analysis of the humanitarian sector, found that in both Liberia and Sierra Leone women died in greater numbers than men at the beginning of the outbreak, in part because they had less access to information and communication channels.

Now in 2018, 4 years later, we are again responding to Ebola outbreaks: This year there have been 2 in the Democratic Republic of Congo, one of the most linguistically diverse countries in the world.

In the area affected by the latest outbreak, Beni Territory, the predominant languages are Swahili, Nande, and Mbuba. There are barely any trained translators for Nande and Mbuba, languages not supported by Google Translate, Microsoft Translator, Facebook, or Amazon.

Community engagement is now a priority activity for some agencies. They write guideline documents and blogs about it, discuss local communication preferences, and make it clear they are trying to learn the lessons of the past. Maps showing what languages are spoken where have proved useful to organisations working to curb the spread of the virus. ...[more]

Meaningful 2-way communication fulfills a vital function in an emergency response, as pivotal as providing food, water, or health services.

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail Rapporteur Mary Marshall

[Communication with the local populations is critical. This is just one of the many challenges for aid agencies. One approach that would aid communication is to have local figures, especially those with seniority who have authority, work together with the aid agencies, as these individuals are most likely to be trusted by the community. - Mod.LK]

- Wed 15 Aug 2018. WHO recommendations for international travellers related to the Ebola virus disease outbreak in the Democratic Republic of the Congo [WHO INT, edited]
http://origin.who.int/ith/evd-travel-advice-final-15-08-2018-final.pdf

The risk of contracting Ebola virus disease to most travellers is low. Travellers in the affected areas should avoid exposure to Ebola virus and practice good hygiene. If symptoms consistent with Ebola virus disease develop, seek immediate medical attention. Travellers in transit with symptoms should advise flight and other transport crews of symptoms and travel history. Risk of disease is low to returning travelers. ...[more]

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail Rapporteur Mary Marshall

[One can find the details of the recommendations at the URL above. The document addresses basic measures that are part of public health hygiene practices. - Mod.LK]

- Thu 16 Aug 2018. No handshakes, no helmets in eastern Congo city preparing for Ebola
[Reuters, edited]
https://www.reuters.com/article/us-health-ebola-congo-goma/no-handshakes-no-helmets-in-eastern-congo-city-preparing-for-ebola-idUSKBN1L123W
[Byline: Fiston Mahamba]

A mobile blood-testing lab, hand-washing stations on street corners, motorcycle taxi drivers forbidden from sharing spare helmets -- if Ebola is coming, the city of Goma in eastern Congo wants to be ready. An outbreak suspected of killing 43 people is spreading across the lush farmlands of eastern Congo, where ethnic and military conflicts threaten to hobble containment efforts.

Goma, a lakeside city of one million people near the Rwandan border, is more than 350 km (220 miles) south from the epicenter of the outbreak in the town of Mangina in North Kivu province, and no cases have been confirmed there [Goma]. But the virus has already spread to neighboring Ituri province, and the number of infected cases is rising daily. Residents in the busy trading hub are taking no chances.

"It's not only me who fears the appearance of Ebola. The whole community here is scared," said shopkeeper Dany Mupenda. "To protect ourselves we stick to the rules of hygiene to avoid being one of the victims of this epidemic."

UNICEF has set up handwashing stations around the city, many of whose streets are built on top of the lava rock left from the eruption of the Mount Nyiragongo volcano in 2002. Health workers check residents' temperatures in public places and at the entrance to the city. The hospital has set up a mobile lab to test suspected cases.

It is the kind of preparation that has become routine in Congo, which has experienced 10 Ebola outbreaks since the virus was discovered on the Ebola River in 1976, altogether killing some 900 people. ...[more]

Patrons of Goma's popular motorcycle taxis must risk speeding helmetless across town. "We are told that it can spread through the sweat of heat, and as our helmets are not worn by one customer only, they allowed customers to ride with no helmet to prevent the spread," said a taximan called Wemba.

[Additional contributions from Edward McAllister (writing) and Angus MacSwan (editing)]

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail Rapporteur Mary Marshall

[Is helmet sharing really a risk? A comparison of deaths from Ebola vs motorcycle deaths and severe injury due to not wearing helmets could be calculated. It may be riding on the motorbike itself presents a risk of contamination. - Mod.LK]

